              {
                "textRuns": [
                  {
                    "value": "Pie and Donut charts are used to show parts of a whole, such as percentages to 100%. Ideally they should only be used when there is a small number of segments (5 or less, otherwise use a bar or column) and each segment can be easily seen; they emphasise percentages and proportions, making them useful for highlighting the relative sizes of different categories. ",
                    "textStyle": {
                      "fontSize": "8pt",
                      "color": "#767676"
                    }
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "textRuns": [
                  {
                    "value": "The decision between a Pie or Donut chart is mostly stylistic - the benefits of using a pie is that you can use a card in the centre circle to display an additional metric such as total.",
                    "textStyle": {
                      "fontSize": "8pt",
                      "color": "#767676"
                    }
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "textRuns": [
                  {
                    "value": "A legend should be included if the data category cannot easily be added to the data label.",
                    "textStyle": {
                      "fontSize": "8pt",
                      "color": "#767676"
                    }
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
